===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|ja|sake}}
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|さけ}}

{{IPAfont|⟨sake<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → {{IPAchar|/sakəɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/sake/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|酒|tr=sake<sub>2</sub>}},<ref name="ONCOJSake">{{R:jpx:ONCOJ|entry=sake/saka|number=L050073}}</ref><ref name="KDJ2Sake">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten Concise}}</ref> from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*sakai}}. Cognate with {{cog|jpx-ryu-pro|*sake|sort=さけ}}. Attested in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 {{CE}}, with the ideographic spelling {{lang|ja|酒}}.<ref name="KDJ2Sake"/> Additionally, appears in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}} and the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' of {{circa2|759 {{CE}}|short=1}}.<ref name="ONCOJSake"/><ref name="KDJ2Sake"/> This is the standalone form of ''saka-'' below.

Various theories exist regarding the ultimate derivation:
* Might be cognate with {{ja-r|栄え|さかえ}}, the {{ja-ryk|栄える|さかえる|to [[flourish]]}}<ref>{{R:Sekai Dai Hyakka Jiten}}</ref><ref name="GYJSake">{{R:Gogen Yurai Jiten|酒／さけ|sake}}</ref>
* Might be derived from {{ja-r|避ける|さける|to [[ward off]], to [[shun]]}}, from the idea that drinking alcohol would ward off cold diseases.<ref name="GYJSake"/>
* Might be derived from or a corruption of {{ja-r|酒|くし|[[rice wine]], [[rice]] [[vodka]], [[sake]]}}; however, the phonological shifts required are completely unexplainable.<ref name="GYJSake"/>
* The final ''-ke'' may be an [[apophony|apophonic]] form of {{inh|ja|ojp|酒|tr=ki<sub>1</sub>}}.<ref name="GYJSake"/>

